<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n13080k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n13" href="#n13080k">N13 (VI.D.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n13all.htm#n13080k"> 80(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ogham and pogham</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">I have often heard this word pronounced of late as <mark>Oggam</mark>, which is certainly wrong. In later times the &ldquo;g&rdquo; often became &ldquo;aspirated,&rdquo; and was not pronounced. The Munstermen pronounced the word as if written &uacute;gham (<i>i.e.</i>, 0om, rhyming with room); in Connacht it would have been most likely pronounced &ldquo;ome,&rdquo; rhyming to home, but the best pronunciation of it in either Irish or English is to leave the &ldquo;g&rdquo; unaspirated, and pronounce it as if rhyming to <i>rogue &apos;em</i>, or <mark><i>p&oacute;g &apos;am</i></mark>. <small> Douglas Hyde, <a name="SEGL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SEGL"><cite title="source">The Story of Early Gaelic Literature</cite></a> (1920) 3n</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05019k" href="c5all.htm#c05019k">VI.C.05:019(k)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
